	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Montreal</placeName> <date>8th May 5625</date>.</p>
				<p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir&#45;</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">I send you herewith<lb/> fifty Dollars which will balance the<lb/> amount of my indebtedness to you for<lb/> Books &#38; printing to date.  The following<lb/> is a statement as per your favors of<lb/> <date>September</date> last &#38;c</p>
				<table rows="12" cols="3">
				<row>
				<cell>&#8220;10 Sets will cost you</cell>
				 <cell>17.</cell>
				<cell>&#36;170</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell> less 20 per cent</cell>
				<cell/>
				<cell><hi rend="underline">  34</hi></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell/>
				<cell/>
				<cell>136</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell> add binding 70 vols</cell>
				<cell>60</cell>
				<cell><hi rend="underline">   42</hi></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell> 6 daily</cell> 
				<cell>3.25&#8212;19.50</cell>
				<cell>178</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell> less 20 per cent</cell> 
				<cell><hi rend="underline">3.80</hi></cell>
				<cell><hi rend="underline">15.70</hi></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell/>
				<cell> 15.70</cell>
				<cell>193.70</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell>Printing Sermon &#38; Biography</cell>
				<cell/>
				<cell><hi rend="underline">  31.00</hi></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell/>
				<cell/>
				<cell>224 70</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell>cr.</cell>
				<cell/>
				<cell/>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell><date>Sep &#39;54</date> By draft</cell>
				<cell> 175</cell>
				<cell/>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell><date>May 55</date> &#8220; Bills</cell>
				<cell>50</cell>
				<cell>225.</cell>
				</row>
				</table>
				<p>leaving 30 cents to my credit&#59; though</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>there will be due you &#36;9 for <persName>Mrs<lb/> Naapers</persName> subscription to the Occident.<lb/>&#8212;I have been hunting everywhere<lb/> to <hi rend="underline">elucidate</hi> this matter&#44; but though<lb/> I have entries of monies paid on your<lb/> account in <date>1860</date> I cannot find that<lb/> I paid <persName>Mr Joseph</persName> that identical amount.<lb/>  But as <persName>Mrs N.</persName> paid&#44; &#38; you did not receive<lb/> the amount I am the defaultee&#44; and<lb/> will send it you another time&#44; as I<lb/> could only readily obtain today &#36;50<lb/> in your currency&#8212;now pretty near<lb/> our own in value.  While I write<lb/> it occurs to me you could pay yourself<lb/> &#38; accommodate me&#44; if you would<lb/> let me draw through you on<lb/> the esteemed editor of the <placeName>N. Y.</placeName> Jewish<lb/> Record who owes me a <add>&#63;</add><lb/> amount <add>Hebrew</add>.  Let me know&#44;<lb/> please&#44; if you would like to do this<lb/> and I will send you the order.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">You would oblige me when<lb/> you send the Occidents to let me have</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>at the same time the subjoined nos of the<lb/> <sic>occident</sic> which I require to complete<lb/> &#42;my pyle&#8212;Except 3&#44; they are all of<lb/> the weekly series and failed to reach<lb/> me through irregularity of the Post Office</p>
				<list type="simple">
				<head></head>
				<item>Vol 14 nos 1&#44;2.</item>
					<item rend="indent(1)">       15 no 5.</item>
					<item rend="indent(1)">       17 nos 23&#44; 25&#44; 26&#44; 28&#44; 31&#44; 43.</item>
					<item rend="indent(1)">       18 nos 6&#44; 12&#44; 40&#44; 41&#44; 47&#44; 49&#44; 51</item>
				</list>
				<p>You can send them by mail&#8212;the weeklies<lb/> can go in one wrapper.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">In a recent letter you ask<lb/> whether something can&#39;t be done with<lb/> the <persName>Benjamins</persName>.  I before wrote you<lb/> enclose your account and I will<lb/> do what I can with <persName>Wm Benjamin</persName><lb/> here.  You also are surprised<lb/> that your subscribers here are&#44; so few&#44; but <add>Hebrew</add> Jews don&#39;t<lb/> increase in <placeName>Canada</placeName>.  If you have<lb/> no field here&#44; be comforted with<lb/> the reflection that neither have I</p>
			<pb n="4"/>
				<p>nor any one else.  It is because I have<lb/> as good a position as a Jew could<lb/> obtain among <add>&#63;</add>&#44; and that my<lb/> position at College has greatly improved<lb/> that I am satisfied with the extent<lb/> of my Jewish field.  I presume<lb/> <persName>Mr Joseph</persName> paid you for his set of<lb/> prayers in sheets&#44; which I duly handed<lb/> him.  I am greatly obliged to you<lb/> for the portrait which I have appropriated<lb/> to myself&#8212;the other one we have I don&#39;t<lb/> think so good.  I send you some<lb/> verses written by an esteemed &#38; talented<lb/> friend <persName>Miss Sarah Livia</persName> of <placeName>London</placeName> on the<lb/> death of my brother <persName>Isaac</persName> <add>&#63;</add> which from<lb/> their religious fervor you may think<lb/> worthy of publishing in the Occident.<lb/>  <persName>Miss Livia</persName> who is not sufficiently known<lb/> to our people has <add>&#63;</add> for some years<lb/> some excellent pieces in prose as well as<lb/> poetry to various <placeName>London</placeName> magazines and<lb/> no doubt&#44; had not her natural retiringness<lb/> been in the way&#44; she would worthily have<lb/> filled the place left vacant by <persName>Grace Aguilar</persName>.  I send<lb/> the lines rather to show that the true <add>&#63;</add> is<lb/> among</p>
				<p rend="Letter cuts off here."></p>
		</body>
